:INFO
Blades Are Not Interchangeable
All double-edge blades fit all safety razors mechanically, but sharpness, \
coating, and thickness vary significantly by brand. The same blade behaves \
very differently in an aggressive razor versus a mild one. Start with a mild \
razor and a moderate blade. Fine-tune the combination after you understand \
your own face, technique, and beard coarseness.

:COUNTER.half
$0.10 to $0.50 Per Blade
vs $3 to $6 per cartridge
|
:COUNTER.half
3 to 5 Shaves
Typical lifespan per blade before replacement

:PATH
Buy a Blade Sampler First
Never buy 100 blades of one brand as a beginner. Purchase a sampler pack \
containing 10 to 20 different brands, 5 to 10 blades each. Shave with each \
brand for at least 3 sessions before judging it. Your ideal blade depends on \
beard coarseness, skin sensitivity, and razor head geometry. A blade that causes \
irritation in one razor may work perfectly in a different head design.

:CHECKLIST
Common Blade Categories
[ ] Sharp and aggressive: Feather Hi-Stainless, Gillette Nacet — best for coarse \
beards and experienced technique
[ ] Medium versatile: Astra Superior Platinum, Voskhod — forgiving for beginners, \
widely available
[ ] Mild and smooth: Derby Extra, Wilkinson Sword Classic — suited to sensitive \
skin and mild razors
[ ] Budget consistent: Shark Super Chrome, Dorco ST-301 — reliable performance \
at the lowest cost per blade

:PATH
Dispose of Blades Safely
Used blades are sharper than new utility knives and must never go into household \
trash unprotected. Store each used blade in the empty paper sleeve it came in, \
or use a dedicated blade bank — a slotted tin that accumulates hundreds of blades \
safely until full, then is disposed of as a sealed unit at a sharps collection point.

:NOTE
The Blade Break-In Effect
Some blades, particularly Feather, are described by experienced shavers as having \
a short break-in period where the first shave feels harsher than subsequent ones. \
If your first session with a new brand felt rough but showed no typical razor burn, \
try it a second time before discarding the brand entirely. The coating on some \
blades smooths after one pass across the face.

:INFO
Razor Aggressiveness and Blade Pairing
Razor aggressiveness is determined by blade gap and blade exposure — how far the \
cutting edge sits from the safety bar. An aggressive razor (large gap) with a very \
sharp blade like Feather can be overwhelming. A mild razor with a moderate blade \
is the forgiving entry point. Match aggressiveness to your current technique level, \
then adjust blade sharpness as confidence grows.

:QUOTE
The right blade is the one that matches your razor, your technique, and your face. That combination is entirely personal.

